FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE, BOVINE - ZAMBIA
*************************************
A ProMED post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
Date: 16 Sept 99
From: ProMED <promed@usa.healthnet.org>
Source: OIE Reporting

See also: 7 May 1999
(Date of last previously reported outbreak: April 1999)
Emergency report
Text of an e-mail received on 31 August 1999 from Dr M.P.C. Mangani,
Director of Animal Production and Health, Ministry of Agriculture, Food and
Fisheries, Lusaka:
Report date: 30 August 1999.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 19 August 1999.
Estimated date of first infection: 1 August 1999.
Outbreaks:
Location: Kazungula, Southern Province (25 15' E, 17 38' S)
No. of outbreaks: 1
Description of affected population: a transhumant herd located on a river
island.
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
species: bovine
susceptible: 500
cases: 300
deaths: 0
destroyed: 0
slaughtered:0
Laboratory where diagnosis was made: OIE Reference Laboratory for foot and
mouth disease (Botswana Vaccine Institute, Gaberone, Botswana).
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: the affected herd is suspected to
have been in contact with young buffaloes from a nearby national game
park.B. Mode of spread: through movement of cattle/buffaloes.
C. Other epidemiological details: surrounding areas are not affected.
Control measures during reporting period:
- control of wildlife reservoirs;
- surveillance has been intensified;
- movement controls.
--
ProMED
e-mail: promed@usa.healthnet.org
